╚═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

NEXUS: "Engineer, network isolation is our first line of defense. The cascade
       failure exposed vulnerabilities in our architecture. Your mission is to
       verify that isolation boundaries are intact - that containers can ONLY
       reach what they're supposed to reach. Security depends on proving the
       negative: confirming what is NOT possible."

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

OBJECTIVE
═════════
Network isolation prevents unauthorized access by placing resources on separate
networks. Traffic cannot cross these boundaries without explicit permission
(a container connected to both networks).

Our station has two security zones:
  - Frontend Zone (172.20.0.0/24): Publicly accessible services
  - Backend Zone (172.21.0.0/24): Protected internal services

Verify that isolation is working correctly.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

TASKS
═════

[ ] Task 1: Map the Trust Boundaries
    Frontend Zone (172.20.0.0/24):
      - client (172.20.0.10) - User workstation
      - server (172.20.0.20) - Web server
      - api (172.20.0.30)    - Application gateway

    Backend Zone (172.21.0.0/24):
      - database (172.21.0.40) - Data storage
      - api (172.21.0.30)      - Backend connection
      - monitor (172.21.0.50)  - Admin access

[ ] Task 2: Verify Client CAN Reach Frontend Services
    docker exec client ping -c 1 server
    docker exec client ping -c 1 api
    docker exec client curl -s http://server | head -5
    docker exec client curl -s http://api:5000/health

[ ] Task 3: Verify Client CANNOT Reach Backend Services
    docker exec client ping -c 1 database
    # Result: Should FAIL (no route or name resolution fails)

    docker exec client ping -c 1 172.21.0.40
    # Result: Should FAIL (no route to host)

[ ] Task 4: Verify Database CANNOT Reach Frontend
    docker exec database sh -c "ping -c 1 172.20.0.10 2>&1 || echo 'Cannot reach client'"
    # Database is protected in both directions!

[ ] Task 5: Test the API Gateway Pattern
    docker exec -it api bash
    ping -c 1 server     # Frontend access
    ping -c 1 database   # Backend access
    ip addr | grep inet  # Show both interfaces
    exit

    # Client -> API -> Database flow
    docker exec client curl -s http://api:5000/db/status

[ ] Task 6: Compare Route Tables
    docker exec client ip route     # Only frontend routes
    docker exec api ip route        # Both frontend AND backend routes
    docker exec database sh -c "ip route 2>/dev/null || cat /proc/net/route"

[ ] Task 7: Verify DNS Does Not Equal Connectivity
    docker exec client dig +short database
    # May resolve (DNS is on both networks)

    docker exec client ping -c 1 172.21.0.40
    # But still cannot connect!

[ ] Task 8: Attempt Route Manipulation (Will Fail)
    docker exec client ip route add 172.21.0.0/24 via 172.20.0.1
    # Should fail - no permission, and gateway won't forward anyway

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

ISOLATION PROTECTS AGAINST
══════════════════════════
Without isolation, an attacker who compromises the web client could:
  - Directly connect to the database
  - Scan the internal network
  - Access other backend services

With isolation:
  - Attacker is confined to frontend network
  - Database is invisible and unreachable
  - Attack surface is reduced to the API only

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

VERIFICATION
════════════
Run: ./verify

Success: You have verified that network isolation is working - the client
cannot reach the database, and the database cannot reach the client.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

